### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

_No response_

### Description

Currently, if we need to call a function within an Angular template, we need to use `@let` to define a variable and the function call must return a value, even if the value is not used. Furthermore, if the $index needs to be used, accessing it within the `@for` declaration doesn't allow the `let` usage for that variable.

More specifically, there currently isn't a "clean" way to do this within a `@for` loop block for an arbitrary number of calls:

```
@for (item of items; track item.id) {
  @let _1 = myCalcFunction1($index);
  @let _2 = myCalcFunction2();

  Item #{{ idx }}: {{ item.name }} ( {{ myCalculatedValue1 }} - {{ myCalculatedValue2 }} )
}
``` 

As demonstrated, the index may or may not matter - I simply want to call a function.

# Example Use Case 1 - FormArrays

Imagine a `@for` loop is being used to iterate over a `FormArray`'s controls. The code-behind would have already spent  processing time looping to build the controls to begin with. Second, the template will already be iterating _again_ over the FormArray. If some _other_ action needs to be taken in the code-behind, it would be much more efficient to allow this to occur **while the template is already iterating the FormArray**:

```
div formArrayName="myFormArray">
  @for (ctl of myFormArray.controls; track ctl) {
    @let _ = doSoethingWhileIteratingFormArray($index);
  ...
```

# Example Use Case 2 - General Debugging, Stats, and API Calls

There may be debugging needs, statistics and usage tacking, API calls, or other use cases where we may want to simply call an arbitrary function while the code is iterating over an array already. This would vastly simplify the need for extra functions, index tracking, subscriptions, and general coordination.

### Proposed solution

Either allow discards to be used within `@for` and `@let` blocks or simply allow void function calls.

Discards in @for let block:

```
@for (item of items; track item.id; let idx = $index, e = $even, _ = myCalcFunction1(idx), _ = myCalcFunction2()) {
  ...
}
```

Discard within @let block:

```
@for (item of items; track item.id; let idx = $index, e = $even) {
  @let _ = myCalcFunction1(idx);
  @let _ = myCalcFunction2();

  ...
}
```

Separate block arguments without let:

```
@for (item of items; track item.id; let idx = $index, e = $even; myCalcFunction1($index), myCalcFunction2()) {
  ...
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Using `@let` blocks to call functions that _must_ return a value. If we need to use the $index value, `let` cannot be used inside the `@for` declaration.

